x4freetext: Experiments performed at the Triangle
Universities Nuclear Laboratory on the campus of Duke
University using a 10 MV FN Tandem Van de Graaff
accelerator.
Each measurement used a single dual-fission
chamber placed in close proximity to the neutron
production source. A special mounting was created to
allow fine adjustments of the position of the fission
chamber relative to the end of the beam line. Using a
fixed spacer, 15.8 mm wide, the fission chambers were
set a fixed distance from the end of the beam line.
Finally, a fixed telescope downstream at 0 degree,
was used to adjust the horizontal and vertical
positioning of the chamber so that it was centered on
the same position as the neutron production source.
This enabled reproducible positioning of the fission
chambers between different measurements. Since 235U
and 239Pu have substantial thermal cross sections, a
cadmium cover(hat) was made that fit over the top of
the fission chambers. The Cd-hat reduces the
room-return neutrons by approximately a factor of 2.
A BC-501A liquid scintillator neutron detector was also
placed about 3 m downstream from the neutron
production source which served as flux monitor and was
used during neutron time-of-flight measurements.
A single dual-fission chamber (DFC) contains a thick
activation target and two thin reference foils of the
same isotope. The body of each DFC has an outer
diameter of  2.50 cm and an overall thickness of
1.73 cm. The total volume of the DFC is about 3.5 cm3.
The efficiency of the FCs were determined by preparing
252Cf sources in the same configuration as the
reference foils. The fission detection efficiency was
Gamma rays from fission products were measured
using lead-shielded High-Purity Germanium detectors
over a period of 1.5-2 months after activation using
a number of different counting cycles.
Fission yields were determined by activation
method using characteristic gamma rays of fission
products.
The 7Li(p,n) 7Be reaction was used to achieve
about 0.5 MeV neutrons. For incident proton energies
greater than 2.372 MeV, the 7Li(p,n)7Be reaction is no
longer monoenergetic, due to the opening of the neutron
emission channel from the first excited state of 7Be
at 429 keV. Neutron production targets for this
reaction were produced by evaporation of lithium
fluoride (LiF) powder onto 19 mm diameter by 0.2 mm
thick aluminum disks. The mass of the LiF varied
between 0.9 and 1.2 mg between the various targets that
were produced. The mean incident neutron energy
achieved on target using this reaction was 0.56 MeV
with a total spread in neutron energy of +-30 keV.
The 3H(p,n) 3He reaction produces monoenergetic
neutrons up to incident proton energies of 8.348 MeV,
resulting in a maximum neutron energy of 7.7 MeV. For
these measurements, this reaction was used to produce
neutrons at about 1.37, 2.37 and 3.60 MeV, with total
energy spreads of +-120, 70 and 70 keV respectively.
The tritiated target consists of a 19 mm diameter by
0.4 mm thick Cu disk on which a 16 mm diameter and
2.2 mg/cm2 thick layer of titanium was evaporated.
Into the Ti layer 2.1 Ci of tritium was absorbed,
giving a ratio of T/Ti >1.5. In order to provide
cooling to the Havar foil and tritiated target, a
helium gas buffer cell (usually pressurized to about
1.5 atm) is used upstream from the production target
foil. The Cu disk and the copper target chamber are
cooled from the outside with separate gas lines of
both compressed and chilled air. For proton beam
currents between 2 and 4 mu-A, a water cooled target
chamber made of copper was used in place of the
stainless steel target chamber.
The reaction 2H(d,n) 3He was used to produce
neutrons with energies of 4.56, 5.5 and 8.9 MeV. The
measurements at these energies had spreads (FWHM) in
the neutron energy of +-250, 140 and 100 keV,
respectively.
The 3H(d,n) 4He reaction was used to produce
neutrons at the nearby energy of 14.8 MeV with an
energy spread of +-75 keV.
The following partial uncertainties are not included in
the total uncertainty (<1% for each):
half-life, counting time, decay time, irradiation time
room-return neutron backgrounds.
The total uncertainty is determined by summing
in quadrature the different components listed below.
photo-peak area
neutron flux correction
HPGe efficiency
fission chamber efficiency (1.5%)
gamma-ray emission probability
target positioning correction  (~1%)
gamma-ray absorption (1.06%)
target mass
coincidence summing
neutron backgrounds (off-energy)
efficiency ratio
gamma-ray absorption  (0.2%)
Data were corrected for
1) Dead time correction   (1%).
2) The photon self-attenuation correction for each
identified fission product for each target at the far
(5 cm) counting position.
3) An average correction for fluctuations in the
neutron flux during irradiation for each fission
product.
In the text in Nucl.Data Sh.,131,319,2016 on p.322
for 7Li(p,n)7Be reaction: `The mean incident neutron
energy achieved on target using this reaction was
0.56 MeV and marks the lowest energy data point in this
set of measurements`. In the tables this energy is
equal 0.58 MeV. This value was used by compiler.
